abstract: Two new books examine how digital technologies are transforming businesses and the economy, and look at the resulting ethical and regulatory concerns.
snippet: Two new books examine how digital technologies are transforming businesses and the economy, and look at the resulting ethical and regulatory concerns.
lead_paragraph: The potential of “big data” and “artificial intelligence” to revolutionize business is routinely hailed by everyone from entrepreneurs to executives at established public companies. Many of these claims have elicited increasing skepticism from the public.

abstract: Thousands of readers told us who they think should lead the Democratic Party — and the country.
snippet: Thousands of readers told us who they think should lead the Democratic Party — and the country.
lead_paragraph: On Sunday, The New York Times’s editorial board will announce which Democratic candidate it’s endorsing in the 2020 presidential race. This year, the board experimented with a new level of openness — publishing transcripts of the interviews with each of the candidates that led to its decision.

abstract: Make no mistake: The departing editor actually changed glossy magazines as we knew them. But to what end?
snippet: Make no mistake: The departing editor actually changed glossy magazines as we knew them. But to what end?
lead_paragraph: On Feb. 28, when Glenda Bailey stands in the Musée des Arts Décoratifs of the Louvre, presiding over the opening of a new photography retrospective, “Harper’s Bazaar: First in Fashion,” it will mark her final act as editor of the storied magazine. Hearst, the publication’s owner, announced on Wednesday her move to become a “global consultant” after 19 years.

abstract: From mass incarceration to mass deportation, our nation remains in deep denial.
snippet: From mass incarceration to mass deportation, our nation remains in deep denial.
lead_paragraph: Ten years have passed since my book, “The New Jim Crow,” was published. I wrote it to challenge our nation to reckon with the recurring cycles of racial reform, retrenchment and rebirth of caste-like systems that have defined our racial history since slavery. It has been an astonishing decade. Everything and nothing has changed.
